<hr />
<dl style="margin-left: 2 em">
  <a name="labarum"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">LABARUM </dt>
  <dd>1) A flag based on the vexillum and combining Christian symbols with those of the 
  Roman military, introduced by the Emperor Constantine in the early 4th Century AD, and 
  later used as an imperial standard - but see '<a href="vxt-dvc1.html#cantabrianlabarum">Cantabrian labarum</a>' (also &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvv2.html#vexillum">vexillum</a>&rsquo;).
  <br>2) The term sometimes used to describe a simple religious banner used in the Roman Catholic Church � see &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvba.html">banner 3)</a>&rsquo;.<br>
  3) A term also used to describe an elaborate (gonfalon-like) banner of the Eastern Orthodox Church (see also �<a href="vxt-dvg2.html#gonfalon">gonfalon</a>�). 
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d4797.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d4797.gif" alt="[labarum]" border="0" height="144" width="71" /></a>&nbsp;
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d4798.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d4798.gif" alt="[labarum]" border="0" height="144" width="68" /></a>&nbsp;
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d4799.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d4799.gif" alt="[labarum]" border="0" height="144" width="68" /></a><br />
  <em>The Labarum of Constantine with two Ancient Roman Labara (fotw)</em>
  <p>
  <em>Please note � not to be confused with a Cantabrian labarum 
  see &ndash; &#39;</em><a href="vxt-dvc1.html#cantabrianlabarum"><em>Cantabrian labarum</em></a><em>&#39;. 
  </em> 
  
  <hr /><a name="label"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">LABEL </dt>
  <dd>1) See &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-c.html#cadency">cadency, mark of</a>&rsquo;.</dd>
  <dd>2) In heraldry a term sometimes also used to describe the tapes which hang below a prelate&rsquo;s mitre � but see &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvsb.html#stringed">stringed</a>&rsquo;.</dd>
  <dd>3) In British usage, the (varyingly detailed) marks of cadency employed on the standards of particular Royal Family members (see also &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvr6.html#royalstandard">royal 
  standard(s) 2)</a>&rsquo;, plus &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-c.html#cadency">cadency, mark of</a>&rsquo; and its following note 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvd2.html#difference">difference 1)</a>&rsquo;  and 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-v.html#variant">variant 1)</a>&rsquo;). 
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d2220.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d2220.gif" alt="[label example]" border="0" height="108" /></a>&nbsp;
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d595.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d595.gif" alt="[label example]" border="0" height="108" /></a>&nbsp;
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d4922.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d4922.gif" alt="[label example]" border="0" height="108" /></a>&nbsp;
  <br />
  <em>British Royal Standards Showing the Labels of <a href="gb_rocha.html">HRH The Prince of Wales</a>, </em> 
  <a href="gb_ropan.html"><em>HRH Princess Anne</em></a><em>, and of <a href="gb_rophw.html">
  HRH Prince Henry</a> (fotw)</em></p></dd>

  <hr /><a name="lambeau"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">LAMBEAU</dt>
  <dd>An alternative heraldic term to dovetailed - see &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvd4.html#dovetailed">dovetailed</a>&rsquo;.
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d3434.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d3434.gif" alt="dovetailed" border="0" height="108"></a> 
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d3434a.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d3434a.gif" alt="dovetailed" border="0" height="108"></a><br />
  <em>Flag and Arms of 
  <a href="no-15-26.html">Stordal</a>, Norway (fotw) </em></dd>
  
  <hr /><a name="lambofgod"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">LAMB OF GOD</dt>
  <dd>See &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dva1.html#agnusdei">agnus dei</a>&rsquo;.
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d376.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d376.gif" alt="[lamb of God]" border="0" height="108" /></a><br />
  <em>Flag of <a href="nl-fr_be.html">Berlikum</a>, The Netherlands (fotw) </em></dd>
  
  <hr /><a name="lance"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">LANCE </dt>
  <dd>A long light-weight spear with which some cavalry regiments were formerly 
  armed, and upon which the standard or guidon was also carried - now restricted 
  to historical or ceremonial use (see also 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvg6.html#guidon">guidon 1) &amp; 2)</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="#lanceflag">lance flag</a>&rsquo;, &lsquo;<a href="#lancepennon">lance pennon 1)</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvs6.html#staff">staff 2)</a>&rsquo; 
  and &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvs6.html#standard">standard 2)</a>&rsquo;). 
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d2334.jpg">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d2334.jpg" alt="[lancer]" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <br><em>Lancer, France 1812 (wiki)</em>
  </dd>
  
  <hr /><a name="lanceflag"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">LANCE FLAG (or PENNANT) </dt>
  <dd>A small flag or pennant, usually swallow-tailed or triangular and of 
  generally simple (bicolour) design, formerly carried below the lance head by 
  those cavalry regiments so armed, or currently by some mounted police units in 
  parade dress, and now restricted to historical/ceremonial use - a lance 
  pennant or pennon (see 
  also &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvb2.html#banneret">banneret 2)</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvp2.html#pennant">pennant 2)</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="#lance">lance</a>&rsquo; and &lsquo;<a href="#lancepennon">lance pennon 1)</a>&rsquo;).
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d193.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d193.gif" alt="[lance flag]" border="0" height="108"></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d3512.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d3512.gif" alt="[lance flag]" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d3514.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d3514.gif" alt="[lance flag]" border="0" height="108" /></a> &nbsp;
  <br />
  <em>Lance Flags, <a href="gb^lp.html">British</a> c1840 (fotw); 
  <a href="de-ba_hi.html#lan">Grand Duchy of Baden</a> c1870 (fotw), 
  Mounted Police, <a href="au_qps.html#pennon">Queensland</a> (fotw)</em>  </p>
  <p><em>Please note that the use of lance-armed cavalry and the 
  general design of their flag or pennant derive from Polish practice &ndash; Poland having 
  been the country from which lance-armed light cavalry was adopted in the late 18th 
  century.</em></p>
  </dd>
  <hr /><a name="lancepennon"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">LANCE PENNON </dt>
  <dd>1)The term for an armigerous lance flag, either fork-tailed or square-ended according to rank, and carried by a medieval mounted 
  warrior (see also 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dva6.html#armigerous">armigerous</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-b.html#bannerofarms">banner of arms</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvb2.html#banneret">banneret 2)</a>&rsquo;, &lsquo;<a href="#lance">lance</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="#lanceflag">lance flag</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvp2.html#pennoncier">pennoncier</a>&rsquo; and &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvh2.html#heraldicstandard">heraldic standard</a>&rsquo;.
  <br>2) See &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-b.html#badgepennon">badge pennon</a>&rsquo;.
  <br>3) See &lsquo;<a href="#lanceflag">lance flag</a>&rsquo;. 
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d1088.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d1088.gif" alt="[Lance pennon]" border="0" height="108"></a>&nbsp;
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d1040.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d1040.gif" alt="Lance pennon" border="0" width="156" height="108" /></a>&nbsp;
    <a href="../images/v/vxt-d668.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d668.gif" alt="[Lance pennon]" border="0" height="108"></a>&nbsp;
  <br /><em>Lance Pennon of Sir Robert Knolles. Knight Banneret c1360, England; 
  Lance Pennon of a Pennoncier (or Knight Bachelor), England 1415; Badge Pennon, England c1460</em>
  </dd>
  
  <hr /><a name="lanceolate"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">LANCEOLATE </dt>
  <dd>(adj) A term that may be used to describe a rounded fly &ndash; but see 
  note below and 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-o.html#ovigal">ogival</a>&rsquo; 
  (also &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvd1.html#descate">descate</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvg6.html#guidon">guidon 3)</a>&rsquo;, 
  &rsquo;<a href="vxt-dvf5.html#fly">fly</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvs6.html#standard">standard 4)</a>&rsquo; and &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvh2.html#heraldicstandard">heraldic standard</a>&rsquo;).
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d195b.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d195b.gif" alt="Lesna, Poland" border="0" width="190" height="105" /></a>
  <br /><em>Flag of <a href="pl-ds0ls.html">Le&#347;na</a>, Poland (fotw)</em></p>
  <p><em>Please note that the differences between &ldquo;</em><a href="vxt-dv-o.html#ogival"><em>ogival</em></a><em>&rdquo; and &ldquo;lanceolate&rdquo; are 
  often very slight, and we suggest that both entries be consulted.</em></p>
  </dd>
  
  <hr /><a name="landesfarben"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">LANDESFARBEN</dt>
  <dd> See '<a href="vxt-dv-n.html#nationalcolors">national colours 2)</a>' and 
  '<a href="vxt-dvs7.html#statecolor">state colours 3)</a>' (also 
  '<a href="vxt-dvl2.html#liverycolors">livery colours</a>').
  <p>
