  <hr /><a name="langued"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">LANGUED </dt>
  <dd>The heraldic term used when the tongue of the beast, if shown, is of different tincture 
  than the rest of the body (see also &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dva4.html#argent">armed 2)</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dva6.html#armedandlangued">armed and langued</a>&rsquo;,   
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dva8.html#attired">attired</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvb4.html#beaked">beaked</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvm2.html#membered">membered</a>&rsquo; and 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvt1.html#tincture">tincture</a>&rsquo;).
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d777.gif">
<img src="../images/v/vxt-d777.gif" alt="&Ouml;sterg&ouml;tland, Sweden" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d777a.gif">
<img src="../images/v/vxt-d777a.gif" alt="Aalter, Belgium" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d777b.gif">
<img src="../images/v/vxt-d777b.gif" alt="Uri, Switzerland" border="0" height="108" /></a>

  <br /><em>Flag of <a href="se-05.html">&Ouml;sterg&ouml;tland</a>, Sweden (fotw); Flag of 
  <a href="be-voval.html">Aalter</a>, Belgium (fotw); Flag of 
  <a href="ch-ur.html">Uri</a>, Switzerland (fotw)</em>  
  </dd>
    <dd>
  <hr /><a name="lanyard"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">LANYARD</dt>
  <dd>1) In French military usage and in some others &ndash; and a translation of fourrag&egrave;re 
  &ndash; the term for those cords and tassels that are worn on military uniforms to signify the 
  award of a unit decoration, and may decorate that unit's military colour &ndash; see 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvc8.html#cord">cord 1)</a>&rsquo; 
  and &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dva1.html#aiguillette">aiguillette</a>&rsquo; 
  (also &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvc5.html#color">colour 2)</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvc9.html#cravat">cravat 1)</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-j.html#jackofhonor">jack of honour</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-l.html#lanyardpennant">lanyard pennant</a>&rsquo; and 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-t.html#tassels">tassels</a>&rsquo;).<br />
  2) See &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-h.html#halyard">halyard</a>&rsquo;.<br />
  3) See &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvd4.html#dressknot">dress knot</a>&rsquo; and its following note.
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d1419.jpg">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d1419.jpg" alt="[fourang&#232;re]" border="0" height="108" /></a><br />
  <em>(marlow white)</em>
  </dd>
  
   <hr />
  <a name="lanyardpennant"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">LANYARD PENNANT
  <dd>In French Naval usage, the term &ndash; and in the language of that country a flamme de fourrag�re &ndash; 
  for a tapered pennant in various colours, charged with the Croix de Guerre 
  and having a rounded (or lanceolate) fly, which is flown to indicate that a vessel has received 
  citations for a certain number of military decorations (see also &lsquo;cravat 1) and its following 
  note, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-f.html#fanion">fanion 3)</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-j.html#jackofhonor">jack of honour</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="#lanceolate">lanceolate</a>&rsquo; , 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-l.html#lanyard">lanyard 1)</a>&rsquo; and 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvp2.html#pennant">pennant 2)</a>&rsquo;). 
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d196.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d196.gif" alt="[Lanyard pennants]" border="0" width="578" height="106" /></a><br />
  <em>Six citations for the <a href="fr~hjck.html#lan">Legion d&rsquo;Honneur</a>, 1914-18 (fotw); 4-5 Citations for the 
  <a href="fr~hjck.html#lan">M&eacute;daille Militaire</a> 1939-45 (fotw)</em>  </p>
  </dd>
  <hr /><a name="lapelflag"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">LAPEL FLAG (or PIN)</dt>
  <dd>1) A metal or plastic flag &ndash; sometimes showing a badge or coat of arms 
  below - worn on the dress or coat lapel as a patriotic or political symbol, 
  originally characteristic of the former Soviet Union and of the United States, 
  but now widely used elsewhere &ndash; a flag badge or flag pin.</dd>
  <dd>2) A paper flag see &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvf2.html#flagday">flag day 2)</a>&rsquo;. <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d899b.jpg">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d899b.jpg" alt="[flag pin]" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d899a.jpg">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d899a.jpg" alt="[flag pin]" border="0" height="108" /></a><br /><em>Two flag pins (worldflags4u)</em></dd>
  
  <hr/><a name="lapped"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">LAPPED</dt>
  <dd>A term sometimes incorrectly used to describe the leaves of a rose in place 
  of the heraldic barbed &ndash; see &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvb2.html#barbed">barbed</a>&rsquo;.</dd>
  
  <hr/><a name="lappets"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">LAPPETS</dt>
  <dd>The heraldic term sometimes used to describe the tapes which hang below a bishop�s mitre � but see �<a href="vxt-dvsb.html#stringed">stringed</a>� (also �<a href="vxt-dvm3.html#mitre">mitre</a>�).  
  <p class="style1">
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d3344a.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d3344a.gif" alt="[lappets]" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d3344.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d3344.gif" alt="[lappets]" border="0" height="108" /></a><br />
  <em>Arms and Flag of <a href="pt-brgrd.html">Real</a>, Braga, Portugal (fotw)</em></dd>
  
  <hr/><a name="larmes"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">LARMES</dt>
  <dd>An alternative heraldic term to gouttes - see &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvg2.html#gouttes">gouttes</a>&rsquo;.
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d378a.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d378a.gif" alt="[gutty / larmes]" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d378.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d378.gif" alt="[larmes]" border="0" height="108" /></a><br />
  <em>Arms and Flag of <a href="no-12-42.html">Samnanger</a>, Norway (fotw) </em></dd>
  
  <hr/><a name="lategothicshield"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">LATE-GOTHIC (or LATE-GOTHIC-STYLE) SHIELD </dt>
  <dd>Terms sometimes used (albeit inaccurately) in vexillology to describe a round-bottomed or Spanish-style shield - 
  but see note below (also &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvr1.html#rectangularshield">rectangular shield</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvs3.html#shield">shield 2)</a>&rsquo; and 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvs5.html#spanishstyleshield">spanish-style shield</a>&rsquo;).
  <p>
  <i>Please note that in vexillology the terms Gothic and late-Gothic appear to be used indiscriminately 
  to describe either a pointed or a round-bottomed shield, and the Editors suggest 
  therefore, that both these terms, if used at all, should be restricted to those with a pointed base.</i>
  </dd>
  
  <hr/><a name="latemedievalshield"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">LATE MEDIEVAL SHIELD</dt>
  <dd>See &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvr2.html#renaissanceshield">Renaissance shield</a>&rsquo;.
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d4667.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d4667.gif" alt="[Dachau]" border="0" height="108" /></a><br />
  <em>Arms of <a href="de-dc-dc.html#c">Dachau</a>, Germany (fotw) </em></dd>

  <hr/><a name="latincross"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">LATIN CROSS</dt>
  <dd>The heraldic term for a cross that does not usually extend to the edges of a shield, flag, panel or flag, but whose horizontal arm is shorter than its vertical and which is set above the centre line � a long cross (see also &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvg4.html#greekcross">Greek cross</a>&rsquo; and &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvcq.html#cross">cross 2)</a>&rsquo;).  
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d3154.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d3154.gif" alt="[Latin cross]" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d3154a.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d3154a.gif" alt="[Latin cross]" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d4568.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d4568.gif" alt="[Latin cross]" border="0" height="108" /></a><br />
  <em>Flag and Arms of <a href="pt-mgdva.html">Vila de Ala</a>, Portugal (fotw);
  Flag of <a href="co-boylu.html">La Uvita</a>, Colombia (fotw) 
  <p>
  Notes<br>
  a) Unless referring to a plain cross, this term should always be accompanied by a further description, for example a �Latin cross 
  fleury� as illustrated below.
</em>
<p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d4569.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d4569.gif" alt="[Latin cross]" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d4569a.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d4569a.gif" alt="[Latin cross]" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <br>
  <em>Flag and Arms of <a href="pt-bnv.html">Benavente</a>, Portugal (fotw) 
  <p>
    b) In vexillological terms a Latin cross throughout becomes an off-centred 
  or Scandinavian-type cross � see &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-o.html#offcenteredcross">off-centered cross 2)</a>&rsquo; 
  and
  <em>�<a href="vxt-dv-o.html#offcenteredcross">off-centered cross 3)</a>�</em>
  (also &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvt1.html#throughout">throughout</a>&rsquo;).
  <p style="height: 131px">
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d4570.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d4570.gif" alt="[Latin cross]" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <em>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d4570a.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d4570a.gif" alt="[Latin cross]" border="0" height="108" /></a></em><br>
  Flag and Arms of <a href="hr-pn-pu.html">Pula</a>, Croatia (fotw)
  </em>
  </dd>
  
  <hr/><a name="latincrossbottony"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">LATIN CROSS BOTTONY</dt>
  <dd>The heraldic term for a cross of victory - see &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvcs.html#crossvictory">cross of victory</a>&rsquo;.
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d2634.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d2634.gif" alt="[Latin cross bottony]" border="0" height="108" /></a><br />
  <em>Flag of <a href="es-o.html">Asturias</a>, Spain (fotw)</em>
  </dd>
 
  <hr/><a name="latincrossthroughout"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">LATIN CROSS THROUGHOUT</dt>
  <dd>See &lsquo;<a href="#latincross">Latin cross</a>&rsquo;, and 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-o.html#offcenteredcross">off-centred cross 2)</a>&rsquo; with its 
  following note.
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d4800.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d4800.gif" alt="[Latin cross throughout]" border="0" height="108" /></a><br />
  <em>Merchant Flag c1650 <a href="lv_riga.html#17th">Riga</a>, Latvia (fotw)</em>
  </dd>
   
  <hr/><a name="lattice"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">LATTICE</dt>
  <dd>1) In vexillology a pattern of interlaced bars forming a (usually but not invariably) diagonal trellis.
  <br>2) In heraldry see &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvf8.html#fretty">fretty</a>&rsquo; 
  and �<a href="vxt-dv-l.html#latticed">latticed</a>�. 
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d4378.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d4378.gif" alt="[lattice example]" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d2785a.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d2785a.gif" alt="[lattice example]" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d2785.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d2785.gif" alt="[lattice example]" border="0" height="108" /></a><br />
  <em>Flag of <a href="cz-pv-pv.html">Prost&#283;jov</a>, Czechia (fotw); 
  Arms and Flag of <a href="de-od-gl.html">Glinde</a>, Germany (fotw)</em>
  </dd>
   
  <hr/><a name="latticed"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">LATTICED</dt>
  <dd>The heraldic term used to describe a pattern of interlaced bars resembling fretty, 
  but with those bars placed vertically and horizontally as in a portcullis - portcullised � 
  but see &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvf8.html#fretty">fretty</a>&rsquo; (also &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvg4.html#gridiron">gridiron</a>&rsquo;).
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d4469.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d4469.gif" alt="[latticed example]" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d4470.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d4470.gif" alt="[latticed example]" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d4471.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d4471.gif" alt="[latticed example]" border="0" height="108" /></a><br />
  <em>Flag and Arms of <a href="pt-mfreg.html#gr">Gradil</a>, Portugal (fotw & 
  <a href="https://www.heraldry-wiki.com/heraldrywiki/wiki/Gradil">Herladry-Wiki</a>); 
  Ensign of the <a href="gb~yhcyc.html">House of Commons YC</a>, UK (fotw)</em>
  </dd>
   
  <hr /><a name="launchingflags"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">LAUNCHING FLAGS </dt>
  <dd>Those flags flown from a vessel that is being launched prior to fitting out, 
  and which in naval usage are generally (but not invariably) of a prescribed type 
  and sequence (see also &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvd4.html#dressinglines">dressing lines</a>&rsquo; and 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvf2.html#flagexchange">flag exchange&rsquo;</a>. 
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d421.jpg">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d421.jpg" alt="[launching flags]" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <br /><em>Launching of HMS St Albans 1747, UK (<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/HMS_St_Albans_(1747)">Wikipedia</a>)</em>
  <em>
  <p>
  Notes
  <br>
  a) The flags flown in the above illustration are i) in the bow a Union Jack, ii) at the fore a Flag of the Lord High Admiral, iii) at the main a Royal Standard and iv) at the mizzen a second Union Jack, with the suite completed by a pre-1801 Red Ensign at the stern.
  <br>b) This combination was usual (in the UK) for the launching of a warship in this era, and is still flown (but with a White Ensign) when HM The Queen is aboard a naval ship � see �<a href="vxt-dva3.html#anchorflag">anchor flag</a>� and its following notes
  </em>  </dd>
  
  <hr /><a name="layucolors"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">LAY UP (or LAYING UP) COLOURS (or COLORS) </dt>
  <dd>(v) The ceremonial deposit of regimental, unit, service or national colours 
  in a church, cathedral or museum when they they are ready for replacement, or when the regiment 
  or military organisation concerned is disbanded (see also 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvc5.html#color">colour 2)</a>&rsquo; and 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvc5.html#colors">colours 2)</a>&rsquo;.
  </dd>
  <hr/><a name="layeredcross"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">LAYERED CROSS</dt>
  <dd>A term that may be used to describe a cross whose horizontal arm differs in colour 
  from its vertical as in the flag of the former Netherlands Antilles (see also &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvcq.html#cross">cross 1)</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="#layeredsaltire">layered saltire</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvt5.html#trinitarian">trinitarian cross</a>&rsquo;
  and &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvt5.html#tripartite">tripartite</a>&rsquo;).  
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d679.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d679.gif" alt="Netherland Antilles" border="0" width="158" height="105" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d679b.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d679b.gif" alt="Belov, Czechia" border="0" width="158" height="105" /></a>
  <br />
  <em>Flag of the <a href="an.html">Netherlands Antilles</a> 1986 - 2010 (fotw); 
  Flag of <a href="cz-km-be.html">B&#283;lov</a>, Czechia (fotw) </em></p>  

  <p><em>Notes<br>a) This term has been introduced by the 
  Editors as no established alternative could be found.<br>b) 
  It should only be used in the 
  description of flags as illustrated above, and does not include crosses which show two colours 
  because of a fimbriation, or are divided in ways other than those shown.</em></p>
	</dd>
  <hr/><a name="layeredsaltire"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">LAYERED SALTIRE</dt>
  <dd>A term that may be used to describe any saltire where an arm of one colour overlays (or 
  apparently overlays) an arm of a different colour as in the examples given below (see also 
  &lsquo;<a href="#layeredcross">layered cross</a>&rsquo;, &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvs0.html#saltire">saltire</a>&rsquo; 
  and &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvt5.html#tripartite">tripartite</a>&rsquo;).  
  
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d680.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d680.gif" alt="Rubi, Spain" border="0" width="158" height="105" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d680a.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d680a.gif" alt="Horni Cerekev, Czechia" border="0" width="158" height="105" /></a>&nbsp;
  <br />
  <em>Flag of <a href="es-b-rub.html">Rubi</a>, Spain (fotw); Flag of 
  <a href="cz-pe-hc.html">Horn&iacute; Cerekev</a>, Czechia (fotw)</em></p>

  <p><em>Notes<br>a) This term has been 
  introduced by the Editors as no established alternative could be found.<br>
  b) It should only be used in the
   description of flags as illustrated above, and does not include saltires which show two 
   colours because of a fimbriation, or are divided in ways other than those shown.</em></p>
   </dd>
   
